What is so challenging about this case is that the situation isn=E2=80=99t =
about one monopoly =E2=80=94 like, say, Microsoft versus OEMs in the 1990s =
=E2=80=94 pushing around a bunch of commoditized counterparts in the value =
chain; Apple=E2=80=99s power is arguably even greater than Google=E2=80=99s=
. That, though, is why Google=E2=80=99s approach was so smart: they basical=
ly bought off Apple, which, thanks to its distribution and its resources, i=
s actually the entity best positioned to directly compete with Google. That=
=E2=80=99s why I brought up the iPhone vs Android fight of a decade ago, an=
d Apple Maps. We did have real competition between these two giants, and we=
 got rapid smartphone innovation and dueling Maps services out of it. Googl=
e=E2=80=99s response, though, wasn=E2=80=99t to continue the fight, but to =
co-opt their opponent (the distribution deal did start before the iPhone, b=
ut its importance has skyrocketed over the last decade).

Again, this was very smart! Anti-competitive behavior usually is; it also e=
xplains why I called the Article =E2=80=9CFriendly Google and Enemy Remedie=
s=E2=80=9D: do we want Google buying would-be competitors off, or do we wan=
t them to be forced to fight for their position? In a vacuum it=E2=80=99s o=
bviously easy to say =E2=80=9Cfight=E2=80=9D, but as the emailer points out=
